Alternative forms[edit]

  • gaitō, guaitō, guaytō

Etymology[edit]

From Frankish *wahtjan, *wahtōn (“to guard, protect”).

Verb[edit]

wactō (present infinitive wactāre, perfect active wactāvī, supine wactātum); first conjugation[1][2]

  1. (Medieval Latin) I keep watch, perform guard duty
  2. (Medieval Latin) I guard, watch over
  3. (Medieval Latin) I lie in wait, ambush

Descendants[edit]

  • Old French: gaiter, guaitier, gaitier, guaiter, gueter, waiter, waitier
    • Middle French: gaitier, gaiter, guetier, guetter
      • French: guetter
    • → Middle English: wayten, waiten
      • English: wait
  • Old Occitan: guaitar
    • Catalan: guaitar, goitar (Pons, Sort, Mallorca)
    • Occitan: guaitar, güeitar, aueitar, uardar, uerdar, guardar (Gascon), gardar (Lengadocian)
